<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-415-578  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 415 578.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Software Engineering  July 1989 v15 n7p854(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multisystem coupling by a combination of data sharing and datapartitioning.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wolf, Joel L.; Dias, Daniel M.; Iyer, Balakrishna R.; Yu, PhilipS.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A hybrid approach for database distribution in a multisystempartitioned database system is developed that combines thefunctioning and advantages of data sharing and data partitioning.andO;The use of multiple processing systems, for such activities astransaction processing, requires either sharing a single databaseor partitioning of a database to each of the systems.andP;  The newapproach is based on a simulated annealing heuristic thatoptimizes database performance on the multisystem by determiningwhich databases should be shared, which should be private to asingle system, and how to partition and route transactions betweendatabases.andP;  The heuristic minimizes computation time and overheadas well as balancing loads between linked systems.andP;  Details of thesimulated annealing and overhead optimization strategies aredescribed.andP;  Implementation on an IBM IMS database managementsystem is evaluated.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Research and DevelopmentSystem DesignParallel AlgorithmsDistributed Data BasesDistribution ManagementHeuristic MethodsData Base Management Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraph.andO;Caption:   Multisystem function shipping architecture. (chart)Multisystem data sharing with centralized locking. (chart)Overhead optimization for balanced case. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>